<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karthik, Kamimura &amp; Kalleshwaraswamy" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Diplatyidae" genus="Diplatys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diplatys sahyadriensis" order="Dermaptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadriensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Diplatys sahyadriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the type locality: the specimen was collected from the Sahyadri Ranges, which is a gateway to the Western Ghats of Karnataka.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Only known from Shivamogga, Karnataka, India.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="bioecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bioecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
The male specimen (holotype) was collected from whorls of sugarcane 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Saccharum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saccharum officinarum" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="officinarum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Saccharum officinarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName family="Gramineae" genus="Saccharum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="phylum">Angiospermae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Saccharum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Gramineae</taxonomicName>
). The collection site is in a mixed area of sugarcane and paddy fields. Faecal pellets were seen on the leaves of sugarcane, suggesting that specimen had been in that place for some time, possibly taking advantage of this shaded spot.
</paragraph>
